text.tspan: Eszter Somogyi, Lisa Jacquey ,Kevin J. ORegan,

flowRoot.flowPara: The model is tested as the controller of a simulated simple planar robot composed of two kinematic 3DoF arms exploring own body in a 2D environment.

Newborn children immediately start to play with is their own body. Thus they autonomously form a sensorimotor map and a repertoire of actions that constitutes the core of future cognitive and motor development. We propose the computational hypothesis that this acquisition of early knowledge is guided by goals autonomously generated and set on the basis of intrinsic motivations.

In the model the internal layer for the clustering of sensory inputs (Goal generator) and the other one for the selection of goals (Goal selector) share the same topological structure. When the activities of the two layers overlap (match) it is computed by the system as an hint that the given sensory state is contingent to what was choosen to be done.

1) a SOM for the acquisition of abstract representations based on the sensory input (touch); 2) a SoftMax selection for choosing goals on the basis of competence-based intrinsic motivations; 3) an ESN controlling the movements of the robot; 4) a predictor of goal reaching to measure competence; 5) a generator of the competence-based signal biasing the activity of the other components.

Santucci, V. G., Baldassarre, G., and Mirolli, M. (2016). GRAIL: a Goal-discovering Robotic Architecture for Intrinsically-motivated Learning. IEEE Transactions on Cognitive and Developmental Systems 8, 214231
